    ('2859','Education','Laurie Vanderploeg','Director, Office of Special Education Programs',NULL,NULL,'155000','2018-11-05 00:00:00',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,3,'laurie-vanderploeg',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'education',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'The Office of Special Education and Rehabilitative Services is excited to announce that Laurie VanderPloeg is joining the team as Director for the Office of Special Education Programs (OSEP). We have full confidence that Laurie‚Äôs depth of knowledge and experience as well as her dedication to preparing students for success will move us forward in our commitment to raise expectations and improve outcomes for infants, toddlers, children and youth with disabilities across the country.

Laurie has dedicated the past 38 years to ensuring that students with disabilities have access to a high-quality education, and her passion for empowering students to succeed began long before she entered the field. Laurie‚Äôs mom was a teacher who helped develop one of the first instructional support models for a school district in Lansing, MI, and her work ethic inspired Laurie to seek a similar career path.

‚ÄúMy mom was my first mentor and role model,‚Äù Laurie said. ‚ÄúI watched her commitment to her profession and observed her passion for meeting the individual needs of students.‚Äù

During the four years she spent earning her Bachelor of Science degree at Grand Valley State University in Grand Rapids, MI, Laurie‚Äôs passion for meeting the needs of students with disabilities grew. After she graduated in 1976, she kicked off her career by working with high school students as a special education teacher at Wayland Union Schools.

Laurie‚Äôs experience in the field of special education expands far beyond the classroom. After teaching high schoolers and middle schoolers for 15 years, Laurie returned to Grand Valley to earn her master‚Äôs degree in special education administration, which has proven valuable in her work. She has since served as supervisor of special education for Grand Rapids Public School District, special education consultant with the Michigan Department of Corrections, and most recently as director of special education for Kent Intermediate School District. She also plays a vital role in helping special education administrators develop strong leadership competencies by teaching classes in Grand Valley‚Äôs Special Education Administration Program.','Department of Education','https://sites.ed.gov/osers/2018/10/announcing-new-osep-director/',NULL,'Vanderploeg',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),
